1.	What is DFS? 
DFS (Depth-First Search) is a graph traversal algorithm that explores one branch completely before backtracking. 
	It uses a Stack data structure. 
DFS goes deep into the graph first and then returns back. 
Steps of DFS 
1.	Start from source node. 
2.	Mark node as visited. 
3.	Push node into stack. 
4.	Visit unvisited adjacent node. 
5.	Repeat until all nodes are visited. 
Applications 
	Path finding 
	Cycle detection 
	Maze solving 
	Topological sorting  
2.	Write a Parallel Depth First Search (DFS) Algorithm using OpenMP 
Parallel DFS Algorithm using OpenMP 
#include <stdio.h> 
#include <omp.h> 
 
#define MAX 100 
 
int visited[MAX]; 
 
void parallelDFS(int graph[MAX][MAX], int node, int n) {     visited[node] = 1; 
 
    printf("Visited %d by thread %d\n",            node, omp_get_thread_num()); 
 
    #pragma omp parallel for 
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) { 
 
        if(graph[node][i] && !visited[i]) { 
 
            #pragma omp critical 
            {                 if(!visited[i]) {                     parallelDFS(graph, i, n); 
                } 
            } 
        } 
    } 
} 
Explanation 
•	#pragma omp parallel for distributes work among threads. 
•	Different threads explore different adjacent nodes simultaneously. 
•	critical section prevents multiple threads from modifying shared data at the same time.  
3.	What is the advantage of using parallel programming in DFS? 
Advantages 
1.	Faster graph traversal 
2.	Better CPU utilization 
3.	Efficient for large graphs 
4.	Reduced execution time 
5.	Multiple nodes processed simultaneously 
“Parallel programming improves DFS performance by executing multiple tasks simultaneously.”  
4.	How can you parallelize a DFS algorithm using OpenMP? 
DFS can be parallelized by dividing graph traversal work among multiple threads. 
Method 
•	Use OpenMP directives like: 
#pragma omp parallel for 
•	Different threads process different adjacent nodes simultaneously. 
•	Shared data structures like visited[] must be synchronized properly. 
Steps 
1.	Divide graph into subgraphs/tasks. 
2.	Assign tasks to threads. 
3.	Threads explore nodes independently. 
4.	Synchronize shared resources. 
 
5.	What is a race condition in parallel programming, and how can it be avoided in OpenMP? 
Race Condition 
A race condition occurs when multiple threads access and modify shared data simultaneously, causing incorrect results. 
Example 
Two threads trying to update visited[] at the same time.  
How to Avoid Race Condition in OpenMP? 
Using synchronization directives such as: 
Critical Section 
#pragma omp critical 
Allows only one thread to execute the block at a time.  
Atomic Operation 
#pragma omp atomic 
Safely updates shared variables.  
Barrier 
#pragma omp barrier 
Synchronizes all threads. 
 
